## Overview

Radioberry is a SDR (Software Defined Radio) transceiver that connects to the Raspberry Pi GPIO header. This guide covers installation on **Raspberry Pi OS 32-bit (Legacy, Bookworm)** and resolves common issues including:

- Kernel header mismatches
- 64-bit vs 32-bit kernel conflicts
- Gateware programming failures (255-255 error)
- Service configuration problems

**Tested on:**
- Raspberry Pi 4 Model B
- Radioberry V2 with Cyclone 10 CL016 FPGA
- Raspberry Pi OS (Legacy, 32-bit) Bookworm

## Prerequisites

- Raspberry Pi 4 (recommended)
- Radioberry SDR board
- MicroSD card (16GB minimum)
- 5V/3A power supply for Raspberry Pi
- Internet connection

## Part 1: Base OS Installation

### 1.1 Download and Install Raspberry Pi OS

Download **Raspberry Pi OS (Legacy, 32-bit)** from the official Raspberry Pi website.

### 1.2 Initial Setup

```bash
# Update the system
sudo apt update && sudo apt upgrade -y

# Install essential build tools
sudo apt install -y build-essential dkms git device-tree-compiler
1.3 Force 32-bit Kernel (Critical for Pi 4/5)
Edit the boot configuration:

bash
sudo nano /boot/firmware/config.txt
Add or modify these lines:

ini
# Force 32-bit mode for Radioberry
arm_64bit=0
kernel=kernel7l.img
Reboot:

bash
sudo reboot
Verify:

bash
uname -m
# Should show: armv7l
Part 2: Radioberry Driver Installation
2.1 Install Kernel Headers
bash
sudo apt install -y raspberrypi-kernel-headers

# Verify headers are installed
ls /usr/src/linux-headers-$(uname -r)
2.2 Download Radioberry Source
bash
cd /tmp
git clone https://github.com/pa3gsb/Radioberry-2.x.git
cd Radioberry-2.x
2.3 Build and Install
bash
# Clean previous builds
make clean

# Install for Cyclone 10 CL016 (adjust FPGA type as needed)
sudo make install FPGATYPE=CL016
2.4 Install the Device Tree Overlay
bash
# Copy the overlay
sudo cp /tmp/Radioberry-2.x/SBC/rpi-4/device_driver/driver/radioberry.dtbo /boot/firmware/overlays/

# Configure boot settings
sudo bash -c 'cat >> /boot/firmware/config.txt << EOF

# Radioberry settings
dtparam=spi=off
dtoverlay=radioberry
EOF'

# Reboot
sudo reboot
2.5 Install Radioberry Daemon
bash
# Copy daemon binary
sudo cp /tmp/Radioberry-2.x/SBC/rpi-4/device_driver/firmware/radioberry /usr/local/bin/
sudo chmod +x /usr/local/bin/radioberry

# Fix service permissions
sudo chmod -x /etc/systemd/system/radioberry.service
sudo systemctl daemon-reload
2.6 Start the Service
bash
sudo systemctl enable radioberry
sudo systemctl start radioberry
sudo systemctl status radioberry
Part 3: Post-Installation Configuration
3.1 Fix Device Permissions
Add the ExecStartPre line to the service file:

bash
sudo nano /etc/systemd/system/radioberry.service
Add this line after ExecStart:

ini
ExecStartPre=/bin/sh -c 'chmod 666 /dev/radioberry'
Then:

bash
sudo systemctl daemon-reload
sudo systemctl restart radioberry
3.2 Add User to Required Groups
bash
sudo usermod -a -G gpio,dialout,spi,i2c pi
# Reboot to apply changes
sudo reboot
3.3 Verify Installation
bash
# Check module is loaded
lsmod | grep radioberry

# Check device node
ls -la /dev/radioberry

# Check gateware version (should NOT be 255-255)
sudo radioberry -v

# Check kernel messages
dmesg | grep -i radioberry | tail -20
Part 4: Troubleshooting Common Issues
4.1 Kernel Headers Not Found
Error:

text
make: *** /lib/modules/6.12.47+rpt-rpi-v8/build: No such file or directory
Solution:

bash
# Reinstall kernel headers
sudo apt install --reinstall raspberrypi-kernel-headers

# Create symlink manually if needed
sudo ln -sf /usr/src/linux-headers-$(uname -r) /lib/modules/$(uname -r)/build
4.2 Module Architecture Mismatch (Exec Format Error)
Error:

text
modprobe: ERROR: could not insert 'radioberry': Exec format error
Cause: Running 64-bit kernel with 32-bit module or vice versa.

Solution: Force 32-bit kernel mode:

bash
# Add to /boot/firmware/config.txt
arm_64bit=0
kernel=kernel7l.img

# Reboot
sudo reboot

# Verify
uname -m  # Should show armv7l
4.3 Device Node Not Created
Symptom: Module loads but /dev/radioberry doesn't exist.

Solution:

bash
# Check if overlay is loaded
ls /proc/device-tree/ | grep radio

# If not, reload overlay
sudo dtoverlay radioberry

# Or reboot with correct config
sudo reboot
4.4 Gateware Version 255-255 (FPGA Not Programming)
Symptom:

text
Radioberry gateware version 255-255.
This is the most common critical error. It means the FPGA is not being programmed.

Causes and Solutions:

4.4.1 Wrong Gateware File Size
The gateware file must be the correct size (335,337 bytes for CL016):

bash
# Check gateware size
ls -la /lib/firmware/radioberry.rbf

# If size is wrong (e.g., 276,233 bytes), copy from working source
sudo cp /tmp/Radioberry-2.x/SBC/rpi-4/releases/dev/CL016/radioberry.rbf /lib/firmware/
4.4.2 SPI Configuration Conflict
Radioberry requires dtparam=spi=off (it uses direct GPIO, not SPI):

bash
# Verify in /boot/firmware/config.txt
cat /boot/firmware/config.txt | grep spi

# Should show: dtparam=spi=off
# If it shows "on", change it to "off" and reboot
4.4.3 Kernel Version Incompatibility
Radioberry works reliably with kernel 5.10.103 but may fail with newer kernels (6.12.x).

Check current kernel:

bash
uname -r
If you have a working setup with kernel 5.10.103, install that kernel:

bash
# Install older kernel
sudo apt update
sudo apt install linux-image-5.10.103-v7l+ linux-headers-5.10.103-v7l+

# Remove problematic kernel
sudo apt remove linux-image-6.12.47+rpt-rpi-v7l

# Update bootloader
sudo update-initramfs -u

# Reboot
sudo reboot
4.4.4 Verify Gateware Programming
After fixes, reload the module:

bash
sudo modprobe -r radioberry
sudo modprobe radioberry
sudo dmesg | grep -i radioberry | tail -10
Expected output should show:

text
Radioberry gateware file size: 335337
Then check version:

bash
sudo radioberry -v
Should show a proper version like 73-3 or 94, not 255-255.

4.5 Service Keeps Restarting
Symptom: systemctl status radioberry shows constant restarting.

Solution:

bash
# Check logs
sudo journalctl -u radioberry -n 50 --no-pager

# Ensure daemon binary exists
ls -la /usr/local/bin/radioberry

# Reinstall daemon if missing
sudo cp /tmp/Radioberry-2.x/SBC/rpi-4/device_driver/firmware/radioberry /usr/local/bin/
sudo chmod +x /usr/local/bin/radioberry
Part 5: Verification Checklist
Run this script to verify everything is working:

bash
#!/bin/bash
echo "=== Radioberry Installation Verification ==="

echo -n "1. Kernel Architecture: "
uname -m

echo -n "2. Kernel Version: "
uname -r

echo -n "3. Radioberry Module: "
lsmod | grep -q radioberry && echo "LOADED" || echo "NOT LOADED"

echo -n "4. Device Node: "
[ -e /dev/radioberry ] && echo "EXISTS" || echo "MISSING"

echo -n "5. Device Permissions: "
ls -la /dev/radioberry 2>/dev/null | cut -d' ' -f1

echo -n "6. Device Tree Overlay: "
ls /proc/device-tree/ | grep -q radio && echo "LOADED" || echo "NOT LOADED"

echo -n "7. Service Status: "
sudo systemctl is-active radioberry

echo "8. Gateware Version:"
sudo radioberry -v 2>&1 | grep -i "gateware version"

echo -n "9. Gateware File Size: "
ls -la /lib/firmware/radioberry.rbf 2>/dev/null | awk '{print $5}'

echo "10. Recent Kernel Messages:"
sudo dmesg | grep -i radioberry | tail -3
Part 6: Uninstallation
bash
# Stop and disable service
sudo systemctl stop radioberry
sudo systemctl disable radioberry

# Remove module
sudo modprobe -r radioberry

# Remove files
sudo rm -f /lib/modules/$(uname -r)/kernel/drivers/sdr/radioberry.ko
sudo rm -f /usr/local/bin/radioberry
sudo rm -f /usr/local/bin/pihpsdr
sudo rm -f /usr/local/lib/libwdsp.so
sudo rm -f /lib/firmware/radioberry.rbf
sudo rm -f /etc/systemd/system/radioberry.service
sudo rm -f /etc/init.d/radioberryd
sudo rm -f /boot/firmware/overlays/radioberry.dtbo

# Remove config lines from /boot/firmware/config.txt (manual edit)
sudo nano /boot/firmware/config.txt
# Remove: dtparam=spi=off and dtoverlay=radioberry

# Update module dependencies
sudo depmod -a

# Reboot
sudo reboot
Key Lessons Learned
32-bit kernel is required - The Radioberry driver is compiled for 32-bit ARM. Use arm_64bit=0 and kernel=kernel7l.img in config.txt.

SPI must be OFF - Radioberry uses direct GPIO, not SPI. Set dtparam=spi=off.

Gateware file must be correct size - For CL016, the working gateware is 335,337 bytes. The 276,233 byte version causes the 255-255 error.

Kernel 5.10.103 works reliably - Newer kernels (6.12.x) may have compatibility issues.

Module location matters - Install to /lib/modules/*/kernel/drivers/sdr/, not /extra/.

Device permissions need fixing - Add chmod 666 /dev/radioberry to the service file.

