after restart the permission changing - what to do ?
The permission change is not persistent because it gets reset when the module reloads or the system reboots. You need to make it permanent. Here are three solutions:

Solution 1: Add to Service File (Recommended)
Edit the radioberry service to set permissions on every start:

bash
sudo nano /etc/systemd/system/radioberry.service
Add the ExecStartPre line as shown:

ini
[Unit]
Description=Radioberry SDR
Wants=network-online.target
After=network-online.target

[Service]
Type=forking
User=root
Group=root
ExecStartPre=/bin/sh -c 'chmod 666 /dev/radioberry'
ExecStart=/etc/init.d/radioberryd start
ExecStop=/etc/init.d/radioberryd stop
Restart=always
RestartSec=10

[Install]
WantedBy=multi-user.target
Then reload and restart:

bash
sudo systemctl daemon-reload
sudo systemctl restart radioberry
Solution 2: Create a udev Rule (Most Permanent)
Create a udev rule that sets permissions automatically when the device is created:

bash
sudo nano /etc/udev/rules.d/99-radioberry.rules
Add this line:

text
KERNEL=="radioberry", MODE="0666"
Then reload udev:

bash
sudo udevadm control --reload-rules
sudo udevadm trigger
Solution 3: Add to rc.local (Legacy Method)
bash
sudo nano /etc/rc.local
Add before exit 0:

bash
chmod 666 /dev/radioberry
Verify the Fix
After applying one of the solutions:

bash
# Check permissions
ls -la /dev/radioberry

# Should show: crw-rw-rw- (666 permissions)
Quick Test
You can also check if pi user can access the device:

bash
# Test read access
cat /dev/radioberry 2>&1 | head -c 1 && echo " - Device accessible" || echo " - Device not accessible"

# Run pihpsdr
pihpsdr
Recommendation: Use Solution 1 (service file) or Solution 2 (udev rule). Both will survive reboots and module reloads. The udev rule is the cleanest method as it works at the kernel level whenever the device node is created.

